<p id="comment-truncated-4957-1298386469" class="comment">
In her exquisitely written (like all of her writing always was) Hollow City, The Siege of San Francisco and the Crisis of American Urbanism, photos by Susan Schwartzenberg, a socialogical  and historic expose of what we call 'gentrification',  Rebecca...
</p>
<p id="comment-full-4957-1298386469" class="comment" style="display: none">
In her exquisitely written (like all of her writing always was) Hollow City, The Siege of San Francisco and the Crisis of American Urbanism, photos by Susan Schwartzenberg, a socialogical  and historic expose of what we call 'gentrification',  Rebecca Solnit says she, &quot;...is not sure artists should be held responsible for gentrification; it is not necessarily their fault that wealthy proffessionals follow their lead. After all, creeps tend to follow teenage girls around, but teenage girls niether create nor encourage them. Another way to put it is: redevelopment is like an oil spill, with a single cause and a responsible party; gentrification is like air pollution, a lot of unlinked individuals make contributions whose effect is only cumulatively disastrous. One can blame artists and drivers for those cumulative effects, but those effects are not their intention...it is clearly not talented individual artists but the widespread ambiance created by cafes, nightclubs, galleries, and those who hang out in them--by a visible bohemia, along with &quot;lifestyle&quot; commodities--that seeds gentrification.&quot; With as much respect (and more) that is due Ms. Solnit--and through the years that she wrote for and I read 'Artweek', I looked first and foremost for her articles-- a slight quibble is in order. There were many of us who moved into industrial neighborhoods, long abandonded by that industry, we renewed industry in nowoman or man's land, places long fallow, toxic, ugly, so frightening in their emptiness, in their ghostliness of the industrial age, it was very difficult indeed to lure our patrons, our students or our friends there. The spaces were raw, made barely livable by the artists who could not wait to work on their art. Finishing anything, except the art, was in short supply. So were the restauraunts and nightclubs, and galleries the &quot;lifestyle&quot; was difficult, not an enviable one. The point is, in neighborhoods such as mine at the Dutchboy in East Oakland, we took nothing from anyone. The landlord took from us, gave little in return, and the City was content with the perilous arrangement, for the tax revenues and occasional fines leveed for lack of code compliance on the part of the landlord.  
</p>
